			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>Automated Testing Support for Reactive Domain-Specific Modelling Languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/BartMeyers.html">Bart Meyers</a>, <a href="../profile/JoachimDenil.html">Joachim Denil</a>, <a href="../profile/IstvánDávid.html">István Dávid</a>, <a href="../profile/HansVangheluwe.html">Hans Vangheluwe</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997367">10.1145/2997364.2997367</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s main contribution is automated testing support tailored to reactive DSMLs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> It targets domain-specific modeling languages and their execution behaviors.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> Testing reactive DSMLs requires executing models and observing runtime reactions/behaviors.
</li></ul></li></ul>
